{"query": {"pages": {"5033502": {"lastrevid": 626816715, "pageid": 5033502, "canonicalurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Selznick", "title": "Philip Selznick", "editurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&action=edit", "length": 8847, "contentmodel": "wikitext", "pagelanguage": "en", "touched": "2015-03-30T12:13:44Z", "ns": 0, "fullurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Selznick", "revisions": [{"*": "<p><b>Philip Selznick</b> (January 8, 1919 \u2013 June 12, 2010) was professor of sociology and law at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_California,_Berkeley\" title=\"University of California, Berkeley\">University of California, Berkeley</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cohen2010_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cohen2010-1\"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> A noted author in <a href=\"/wiki/Organizational_theory\" title=\"Organizational theory\">organizational theory</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology_of_law\" title=\"Sociology of law\">sociology of law</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Public_administration\" title=\"Public administration\">public administration</a>, Selznick's work was groundbreaking in several fields in such books as <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Moral_Commonwealth&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"The Moral Commonwealth (page does not exist)\">The Moral Commonwealth</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=TVA_and_the_Grass_Roots&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"TVA and the Grass Roots (page does not exist)\">TVA and the Grass Roots</a></i>, and <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Leadership_in_Administration&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Leadership in Administration (page does not exist)\">Leadership in Administration</a></i>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><div id=\"toctitle\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Career\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Career</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Major_contributions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Major contributions</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Individuals_as_independent_agents\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Individuals as independent agents</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Cooptation_theory\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Cooptation theory</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Sociology_of_law\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sociology of law</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Theories_of_mass_society\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Theories of mass society</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#Selected_publications\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Selected publications</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-8\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-9\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Career\">Career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Selznick received his <a href=\"/wiki/Doctor_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Doctor of Philosophy\">PhD</a> in Sociology in 1947 from <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_University\" title=\"Columbia University\">Columbia University</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cohen2010_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cohen2010-1\"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> He was on the faculty of the University of California, Berkeley, between 1952 and 1984, initially with the Department of Sociology and later with the <a href=\"/wiki/UC_Berkeley_School_of_Law\" title=\"UC Berkeley School of Law\">School of Law</a> as well.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cohen2010_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cohen2010-1\"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Major_contributions\">Major contributions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Major contributions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Selznick was a major proponent of the neo-classical organizational theory movement starting in the 1930s.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ShafritzOtt1996_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShafritzOtt1996-2\"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> One of his most influential papers, entitled \"Foundations of the Theory of Organization\" (1948),<sup id=\"cite_ref-Selznick1948_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Selznick1948-3\"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> laid out his major contributions to organization theory.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Individuals_as_independent_agents\">Individuals as independent agents</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Individuals as independent agents\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In simplified form, Selznick postulated that individuals within organizations can hold dichotomous goal-sets, which makes it difficult for organizations and employees to have the same implicit, rational objectives (as theorized in classical organization movement which was a precursor of Selznick's work).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Selznick1948_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Selznick1948-3\"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cooptation_theory\">Cooptation theory</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Cooptation theory\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Selznick's principle of cooptation is an important precursor to the later developments of organizational ecology and contingency theory.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ShafritzOtt1996_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShafritzOtt1996-2\"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sociology_of_law\">Sociology of law</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Sociology of law\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Selznick has been a major contributor to the sociology of law,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> developing his ideas on legal institutions and their problems and possibilities of responsiveness to their constituencies, from his earlier work on the sociology of formal organisations.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Theories_of_mass_society\">Theories of mass society</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Theories of mass society\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Selznick was first &#8211; anticipating <a href=\"/wiki/Daniel_Bell\" title=\"Daniel Bell\">Daniel Bell</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Shils\" title=\"Edward Shils\">Edward Shils</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Talcott_Parsons\" title=\"Talcott Parsons\">Talcott Parsons</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=William_Kornhauser&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"William Kornhauser (page does not exist)\">William Kornhauser</a> and a host of American social scientists &#8211; to attack the theory of <a href=\"/wiki/Mass_society\" title=\"Mass society\">mass society</a>. His approach, adopted by all the rest, bifurcated the theory and argued that there were two analytically distinct groups of mass society theories:\n</p>\n<ul><li>those who were critics of <a href=\"/wiki/Equalitarianism\" title=\"Equalitarianism\" class=\"mw-redirect\">equalitarianism</a> or who emphasized the role of creative and culture-bearing <a href=\"/wiki/Elite\" title=\"Elite\">elites</a>;</li>\n<li>those who emphasized <a href=\"/wiki/Social_disintegration\" title=\"Social disintegration\">social disintegration</a> and the quality of <a href=\"//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/participation\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:participation\">participation</a> in mass society and <a href=\"/wiki/Mass_organization\" title=\"Mass organization\" class=\"mw-redirect\">mass organizations</a>.</li></ul>\n<p>The first group of theorists is best represented by <a href=\"/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Ortega_y_Gasset\" title=\"Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset\">Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Karl_Mannheim\" title=\"Karl Mannheim\">Karl Mannheim</a>. Each of these theorists located the cause of the advent of mass society in the decline of the social position of creative elites who were responsible for the development and the strength of <a href=\"/wiki/Cultural\" title=\"Cultural\" class=\"mw-redirect\">cultural</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Values\" title=\"Values\" class=\"mw-redirect\">values</a>. Mass society arose when society was no longer directed by an identifiable and stable structure of elites, when the vulgar appetites of the masses supplanted \"the canons of refinement and sober restraint.\" The masses cannot simply take over the role served previously by elites; they can express <a href=\"/wiki/Desire_(philosophy)\" title=\"Desire (philosophy)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">desires</a> but not values.\n</p><p>The second group of mass society theorists, those who emphasized social disintegration and the quality of participation, was best represented by <a href=\"/wiki/Emil_Lederer\" title=\"Emil Lederer\">Emil Lederer</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Erich_Fromm\" title=\"Erich Fromm\">Erich Fromm</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Sigmund_Neumann\" title=\"Sigmund Neumann\">Sigmund Neumann</a>. Selznick argued that these theorists leave the role of elites largely unexamined. They defined mass society as the era of mass man, a type defined not in terms of any relationship to a formally superior or intrinsically more qualified elite, but as the expression of a wider social disintegration. The homogeneous, amorphous, and undifferentiated individuals in the mass resulted from radical <a href=\"/wiki/Social_change\" title=\"Social change\">social changes</a> which rendered old <a href=\"/wiki/Norm_(social)\" title=\"Norm (social)\">norms</a> obsolete and old <a href=\"/wiki/Role\" title=\"Role\">roles</a> meaningless. <a href=\"/wiki/Psychological\" title=\"Psychological\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Psychological</a> deterioration followed on <a href=\"/wiki/Social_disorganization\" title=\"Social disorganization\" class=\"mw-redirect\">social disorganization</a>: 'as <a href=\"/wiki/Family\" title=\"Family\">family</a>, church, and traditional political ties weaken, a psychological atomization takes place.' This type of mass society theory pictures society as a crowd in which irrational, emotional acts predominate. \"The readiness for manipulation by symbols, especially those permitting <a href=\"/wiki/Sado-masochistic\" title=\"Sado-masochistic\" class=\"mw-redirect\">sado-masochistic</a> releases, is characteristic of the mass as of the crowd.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Selected_publications\">Selected publications</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Philip_Selznick&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7\" title=\"Edit section: Selected publications\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li> <span class=\"citation journal\">Selznick, Philip (1943). \"An Approach to a Theory of Bureaucracy\". <i>American Sociological Review</i> <b>8</b> (1): 47\u201354. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//dx.doi.org/10.2307%2F2085448\">10.2307/2085448</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.atitle=An+Approach+to+a+Theory+of+Bureaucracy&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.date=1943&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F2085448&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.jtitle=American+Sociological+Review&amp;rft.pages=47-54&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=8\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> <span class=\"citation journal\">Selznick, Philip (1948). \"Foundations of the Theory of Organization\". <i>American Sociological Review</i> <b>13</b> (1): 25\u201335. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//dx.doi.org/10.2307%2F2086752\">10.2307/2086752</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.atitle=Foundations+of+the+Theory+of+Organization&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.date=1948&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F2086752&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.jtitle=American+Sociological+Review&amp;rft.pages=25-35&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=13\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> <span class=\"citation book\">Selznick, Philip (1949). <i>TVA and the Grass Roots: a Study in the Sociology of Formal Organization</i>. Berkeley: University of California Press. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/2293803\">2293803</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.btitle=TVA+and+the+Grass+Roots%3A+a+Study+in+the+Sociology+of+Formal+Organization&amp;rft.date=1949&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F2293803&amp;rft.place=Berkeley&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> <span class=\"citation book\">Selznick, Philip (1957). <i>Leadership in Administration: a Sociological Interpretation</i>. Evanston, IL: Row, Peterson. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/4800611\">4800611</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.btitle=Leadership+in+Administration%3A+a+Sociological+Interpretation&amp;rft.date=1957&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F4800611&amp;rft.place=Evanston%2C+IL&amp;rft.pub=Row%2C+Peterson&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> <span class=\"citation book\">Selznick, Philip (1960). <i>The Organizational Weapon: a Study of Bolshevik Strategy and Tactics</i>. Glencoe, IL: Free Press. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/1558918\">1558918</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.btitle=The+Organizational+Weapon%3A+a+Study+of+Bolshevik+Strategy+and+Tactics&amp;rft.date=1960&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F1558918&amp;rft.place=Glencoe%2C+IL&amp;rft.pub=Free+Press&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> <span class=\"citation book\">Selznick, Philip; Nonet, Philippe; Vollmer, Howard M. (1969). <i>Law, Society, and Industrial Justice</i>. New York: Russell Sage Foundation. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/62067\">62067</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhilip+Selznick&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft.aulast=Selznick&amp;rft.au=Nonet%2C+Philippe&amp;rft.au=Selznick%2C+Philip&amp;rft.au=Vollmer%2C+Howard+M.&amp;rft.btitle=Law%2C+Society%2C+and+Industrial+Justice&amp;rft.date=1969&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F62067&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Russell+Sage+Foundation&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><span class=\"citation book\">Selznick, Philip (1992). <i>The Moral Commonwealth: Social Theory and the Promise of Community</i>. Berkeley: University of California Press. <a 